ommitted` (committed.go, line 68)\\nEvery call to `WriteCommitted`, `UpdateCommitted`, or `UpdateSummary` invokes `getSessionsBranchEntries()`, which calls `FlattenTree()` on the entire `entire/checkpoints/v1` tree. This tree grows linearly with every checkpoint ever committed. For a repository with 200 checkpoints, this means reading hundreds of tree objects and thousands of blob entries just to add a few files to one shard bucket.\\n\\n### Bottleneck #2: `buildTreeWithChanges` (temporary.go, line 699)\\nEvery call to `WriteTemporary` and `WriteTemporaryTask` calls `buildTreeWithChanges`, which flattens the base tree (the entire repository's HEAD tree). For a repository with 500 files, this reads every tree object in the repo just to modify 3 files.\\n\\n### Bottleneck #3: `addTaskMetadataToTree` (temporary.go, line 291)\\nFlattens the already-rebuilt tree again to add task metadata files, then calls `BuildTreeFromEntries` again.\\n\\n### Why This Is O(N) When It Should Be O(depth)\\n\\nThe tree structure of `entire/checkpoints/v1` is:\\n```\\nroot/\\n  a3/                     <- shard bucket (1 of 256 possible)\\n    b2c4d5e6f7/           <- checkpoint dir\\n      metadata.json\\n      0/\\n        full.jsonl\\n        metadata.json\\n        ...\\n  f1/                     <- another shard bucket (UNCHANGED)\\n    ...\\n  ...\\n```\\n\\nWhen adding checkpoint `a3b2c4d5e6f7`, only the `a3` subtree changes. The root tree changes because `a3`'s hash changes, but all other shard buckets (`f1`, etc.) are unchanged. The current code reads every file in every shard bucket, then rebuilds every tree object. Tree surgery instead:\\n\\n1. Reads the root tree (1 tree object read)\\n2. Finds the `a3` entry (or creates it)\\n3. Reads the `a3` subtree (1 tree object read)\\n4. Creates the new checkpoint subtree from scratch (a few new tree objects)\\n5. Replaces the checkpoint entry in the `a3` subtree\\n6. Creates a new `a3` tree object (1 tree object write)\\n7. Replaces the `a3` entry in the root tree with the new hash\\n8. Creates a new root tree object (1 tree object write)\\n\\nThis is O(depth) = O(3) for the metadata branch, regardless of total checkpoints.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 2. Core New Function: `UpdateSubtree`\\n\\n### Location: `/Users/evisdrenova/code/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/checkpoint/tree_surgery.go` (new file)\\n\\nThis function performs \\\"tree surgery\\\" -- it modifies a subtree at a given path within an existing tree without flattening. The key insight is that you can reuse all unchanged subtree hashes.\\n\\n### Function Signature\\n\\n```go\\n// UpdateSubtree replaces or creates a subtree at the given path within an existing tree.\\n// It walks the tree path, replacing only the entries along the modified path.\\n// All sibling entries at each level retain their original hashes (no re-reading or re-building).\\n//\\n// pathSegments is the directory path split into segments (e.g., [\\\"a3\\\", \\\"b2c4d5e6f7\\\", \\\"0\\\"]).\\n// newEntries are the files to place at the leaf directory (replaces that directory's contents).\\n// If existingEntries is non-nil, they are merged with newEntries (existing entries not in newEntries are kept).\\n//\\n// Returns the new root tree hash.\\nfunc UpdateSubtree(\\n    repo *git.Repository,\\n    rootTreeHash plumbing.Hash,\\n    pathSegments []string,\\n    newEntries []object.TreeEntry,\\n    opts UpdateSubtreeOptions,\\n) (plumbing.Hash, error)\\n\\n// UpdateSubtreeOptions configures the behavior of UpdateSubtree.\\ntype UpdateSubtreeOptions struct {\\n    // MergeMode controls how entries at the leaf directory are handled.\\n    // ReplaceAll replaces the entire directory contents.\\n    // MergeKeepExisting keeps existing entries not overwritten by newEntries.\\n    MergeMode MergeMode\\n\\n    // DeletePaths lists paths (relative to the leaf directory) to delete.\\n    // Only applicable when MergeMode is MergeKeepExisting.\\n    DeletePaths []string\\n}\\n\\ntype MergeMode int\\n\\nconst (\\n    // ReplaceAll replaces the entire leaf directory contents with newEntries.\\n    ReplaceAll MergeMode = iota\\n    // MergeKeepExisting merges newEntries into the existing leaf directory,\\n    // keeping entries not overwritten by newEntries (unless in DeletePaths).\\n    MergeKeepExisting\\n)\\n```\\n\\n### Pseudocode for `UpdateSubtree`\\n\\n```go\\nfunc UpdateSubtree(repo *git.Repository, rootTreeHash plumbing.Hash, pathSegments []string, newEntries []object.TreeEntry, opts UpdateSubtreeOptions) (plumbing.Hash, error) {\\n    if len(pathSegments) == 0 {\\n        // We're at the leaf: build the leaf tree from newEntries\\n        // (optionally merging with existing entries based on MergeMode)\\n        return buildLeafTree(repo, rootTreeHash, newEntries, opts)\\n    }\\n\\n    // Read the current tree at this level\\n    var currentEntries []object.TreeEntry\\n    if rootTreeHash != plumbing.ZeroHash {\\n        tree, err := repo.TreeObject(rootTreeHash)\\n        if err != nil {\\n            return plumbing.ZeroHash, fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to read tree: %w\\\", err)\\n        }\\n        currentEntries = tree.Entries\\n    }\\n\\n    targetDir := pathSegments[0]\\n    remainingPath := pathSegments[1:]\\n\\n    // Find the existing subtree entry for targetDir\\n    var existingSubtreeHash plumbing.Hash\\n    found := false\\n    for _, entry := range currentEntries {\\n        if entry.Name == targetDir && entry.Mode == filemode.Dir {\\n            existingSubtreeHash = entry.Hash\\n            found = true\\n            break\\n        }\\n    }\\n\\n    // Recurse into the subtree\\n    newSubtreeHash, err := UpdateSubtree(repo, existingSubtreeHash, remainingPath, newEntries, opts)\\n    if err != nil {\\n        return plumbing.ZeroHash, err\\n    }\\n\\n    // Build a new tree at this level with the updated subtree entry\\n    var updatedEntries []object.TreeEntry\\n    replaced := false\\n    for _, entry := range currentEntries {\\n        if entry.Name == targetDir {\\n            // Replace with new hash\\n            updatedEntries = append(updatedEntries, object.TreeEntry{\\n                Name: targetDir,\\n                Mode: filemode.Dir,\\n                Hash: newSubtreeHash,\\n            })\\n            replaced = true\\n        } else {\\n            // Keep as-is (reuse hash -- this is the key optimization)\\n            updatedEntries = append(updatedEntries, entry)\\n        }\\n    }\\n    if !found && !replaced {\\n        // New directory -- append\\n        updatedEntries = append(updatedEntries, object.TreeEntry{\\n            Name: targetDir,\\n            Mode: filemode.Dir,\\n            Hash: newSubtreeHash,\\n        })\\n    }\\n\\n    sortTreeEntries(updatedEntries)\\n    return storeTree(repo, updatedEntries)\\n}\\n\\nfunc buildLeafTree(repo *git.Repository, existingTreeHash plumbing.Hash, newEntries []object.TreeEntry, opts UpdateSubtreeOptions) (plumbing.Hash, error) {\\n    if opts.MergeMode == ReplaceAll || existingTreeHash == plumbing.ZeroHash {\\n        // Just build from newEntries\\n        sortTreeEntries(newEntries)\\n        return storeTree(repo, newEntries)\\n    }\\n\\n    // MergeKeepExisting: read existing tree, merge\\n    existingTree, err := repo.TreeObject(existingTreeHash)\\n    if err != nil {\\n        // If can't read, just use newEntries\\n        sortTreeEntries(newEntries)\\n        return storeTree(repo, newEntries)\\n    }\\n\\n    // Build lookup of new entries by name\\n    newByName := make(map[string]object.TreeEntry, len(newEntries))\\n    for _, e := range newEntries {\\n        newByName[e.Name] = e\\n    }\\n\\n    // Build delete set\\n    deleteSet := make(map[string]bool, len(opts.DeletePaths))\\n    for _, p := range opts.DeletePaths {\\n        deleteSet[p] = true\\n    }\\n\\n    // Merge: keep existing unless overwritten or deleted\\n    var merged []object.TreeEntry\\n    for _, existing := range existingTree.Entries {\\n        if deleteSet[existing.Name] {\\n            continue\\n        }\\n        if replacement, ok := newByName[existing.Name]; ok {\\n            merged = append(merged, replacement)\\n            delete(newByName, existing.Name)\\n        } else {\\n            merged = append(merged, existing)\\n        }\\n    }\\n    // Add remaining new entries (ones that didn't replace existing)\\n    for _, e := range newEntries {\\n        if _, stillNew := newByName[e.Name]; stillNew {\\n            merged = append(merged, e)\\n        }\\n    }\\n\\n    sortTreeEntries(merged)\\n    return storeTree(repo, merged)\\n}\\n\\n// storeTree creates a git tree object from entries and stores it in the repo.\\nfunc storeTree(repo *git.Repository, entries []object.TreeEntry) (plumbing.Hash, error) {\\n    tree := &object.Tree{Entries: entries}\\n    obj := repo.Storer.NewEncodedObject()\\n    if err := tree.Encode(obj); err != nil {\\n        return plumbing.ZeroHash, fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to encode tree: %w\\\", err)\\n    }\\n    hash, err := repo.Storer.SetEncodedObject(obj)\\n    if err != nil {\\n        return plumbing.ZeroHash, fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to store tree: %w\\\", err)\\n    }\\n    return hash, nil\\n}\\n```\\n\\n### Second Helper: `UpdateSubtreeMultiPath`\\n\\nFor `buildTreeWithChanges`, we need to handle multiple modified files at different paths. Rather than calling `UpdateSubtree` once per file (which would re-read the tree at each level multiple times), we group changes by directory and apply them in a single pass.\\n\\n```go\\n// TreeChange represents a single file change within a tree.\\ntype TreeChange struct {\\n    Path    string             // Full path (e.g., \\\"src/pkg/handler.go\\\")\\n    Entry   *object.TreeEntry  // New entry (nil = delete)\\n}\\n\\n// ApplyTreeChanges applies multiple file-level changes to a tree efficiently.\\n// Changes are grouped by directory and applied in a single recursive pass.\\n// This is the optimized replacement for FlattenTree + modify + BuildTreeFromEntries\\n// when changes touch only a few files.\\nfunc ApplyTreeChanges(\\n    repo *git.Repository,\\n    rootTreeHash plumbing.Hash,\\n    changes []TreeChange,\\n) (plumbing.Hash, error)\\n```\\n\\nThe implementation groups changes by their first path segment, then recurses into each affected subdirectory. Unchanged subdirectories retain their hashes.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 3. Refactoring `WriteCommitted`\\n\\n### Current Flow (committed.go)\\n```\\nWriteCommitted\\n  -> getSessionsBranchEntries()     // FlattenTree (O(N) where N = total files on branch)\\n  -> writeTaskCheckpointEntries()   // adds to flat map\\n  -> writeStandardCheckpointEntries() // adds to flat map\\n  -> BuildTreeFromEntries()         // rebuilds entire tree (O(N))\\n  -> createCommit()\\n```\\n\\n### New Flow\\n```\\nWriteCommitted\\n  -> getSessionsBranchRef()         // just gets the ref + tree hash (no flatten)\\n  -> buildCheckpointSubtree()       // builds the small subtree for this checkpoint\\n  -> UpdateSubtree(rootTree, [\\\"a3\\\", \\\"b2c4d5e6f7\\\"], subtreeEntries, MergeKeepExisting)\\n  -> createCommit()\\n```\\n\\n### Detailed Changes\\n\\n#### 3.1. New method: `getSessionsBranchRef` (replaces `getSessionsBranchEntries` for the surgery path)\\n\\n```go\\n// getSessionsBranchRef returns the sessions branch reference and root tree hash.\\n// Unlike getSessionsBranchEntries, this does NOT flatten the tree.\\nfunc (s *GitStore) getSessionsBranchRef() (*plumbing.Reference, plumbing.Hash, error) {\\n    refName := plumbing.NewBranchReferenceName(paths.MetadataBranchName)\\n    ref, err := s.repo.Reference(refName, true)\\n    if err != nil {\\n        return nil, plumbing.ZeroHash, fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to get sessions branch reference: %w\\\", err)\\n    }\\n    parentCommit, err := s.repo.CommitObject(ref.Hash())\\n    if err != nil {\\n        return nil, plumbing.ZeroHash, fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to get commit object: %w\\\", err)\\n    }\\n    return ref, parentCommit.TreeHash, nil\\n}\\n```\\n\\n#### 3.2. New method: `buildCheckpointSubtreeEntries` \\n\\nThis builds the entries for a single checkpoint's subtree. It replaces the interaction with the flat entries map. It needs to handle:\\n- Reading existing CheckpointSummary (to find session index)\\n- Building session files\\n- Building task checkpoint files\\n- Building the root-level CheckpointSummary\\n\\n```go\\n// buildCheckpointSubtreeEntries builds the tree entries for a single checkpoint subtree.\\n// Returns the entries to place at the checkpoint path (e.g., a3/b2c4d5e6f7/).\\n// Also returns the shard path segments for UpdateSubtree (e.g., [\\\"a3\\\", \\\"b2c4d5e6f7\\\"]).\\nfunc (s *GitStore) buildCheckpointSubtreeEntries(\\n    rootTreeHash plumbing.Hash,\\n    opts WriteCommittedOptions,\\n) (pathSegments []string, newEntries []object.TreeEntry, deletePaths []string, err error)\\n```\\n\\nKey logic:\\n1. Parse checkpoint ID to get shard path: `opts.CheckpointID.Path()` gives `\\\"a3/b2c4d5e6f7\\\"`, split to `[\\\"a3\\\", \\\"b2c4d5e6f7\\\"]`.\\n2. Try to read the existing checkpoint tree at that path (to handle multi-session updates). Use `tree.Tree(\\\"a3\\\")` then `.Tree(\\\"b2c4d5e6f7\\\")` -- this is 2 tree object reads.\\n3. If existing, read `metadata.json` from that subtree to get `CheckpointSummary`, find session index.\\n4. Build the session files as entries (metadata.json, full.jsonl, prompt.txt, context.md, content_hash.txt) -- these become entries in the `<sessionIndex>/` subdirectory. Build this subdirectory tree.\\n5. Build/update the root-level metadata.json (CheckpointSummary).\\n6. If task checkpoint, build task files.\\n7. Return the complete list of entries for the checkpoint directory.\\n\\n#### 3.3. Rewrite `WriteCommitted`\\n\\n```go\\nfunc (s *GitStore) WriteCommitted(ctx context.Context, opts WriteCommittedOptions) error {\\n    // ... validation (unchanged) ...\\n    \\n    if err := s.ensureSessionsBranch(); err != nil {\\n        return fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to ensure sessions branch: %w\\\", err)\\n    }\\n\\n    ref, rootTreeHash, err := s.getSessionsBranchRef()\\n    if err != nil {\\n        return err\\n    }\\n\\n    // Build the checkpoint subtree\\n    pathSegments, newEntries, deletePaths, err := s.buildCheckpointSubtreeEntries(rootTreeHash, opts)\\n    if err != nil {\\n        return err\\n    }\\n\\n    // Apply tree surgery: only modify the path to this checkpoint\\n    newTreeHash, err := UpdateSubtree(s.repo, rootTreeHash, pathSegments, newEntries, UpdateSubtreeOptions{\\n        MergeMode:   MergeKeepExisting,\\n        DeletePaths: deletePaths,\\n    })\\n    if err != nil {\\n        return err\\n    }\\n\\n    commitMsg := s.buildCommitMessage(opts, \\\"\\\")\\n    newCommitHash, err := s.createCommit(newTreeHash, ref.Hash(), commitMsg, opts.AuthorName, opts.AuthorEmail)\\n    if err != nil {\\n        return err\\n    }\\n\\n    refName := plumbing.NewBranchReferenceName(paths.MetadataBranchName)\\n    newRef := plumbing.NewHashReference(refName, newCommitHash)\\n    return s.repo.Storer.SetReference(newRef)\\n}\\n```\\n\\n#### 3.4. Similarly refactor `UpdateCommitted` and `UpdateSummary`\\n\\nThese follow the same pattern: replace `getSessionsBranchEntries()` + `BuildTreeFromEntries()` with `getSessionsBranchRef()` + `UpdateSubtree()`.\\n\\nFor `UpdateCommitted`, the path is `[shard[:2], shard[2:], sessionIndex]` and the new entries are the replaced transcript/prompt/context files.\\n\\nFor `UpdateSummary`, the path is `[shard[:2], shard[2:], sessionIndex]` and only the metadata.json is replaced.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 4. Refactoring `buildTreeWithChanges` (for `WriteTemporary`)\\n\\n### Current Flow\\n```\\nbuildTreeWithChanges\\n  -> FlattenTree(baseTree)           // O(N) where N = all files in repo\\n  -> modify entries (add/delete)     // O(changed files)\\n  -> BuildTreeFromEntries(entries)   // O(N) rebuild entire tree\\n```\\n\\n### New Flow\\n```\\nbuildTreeWithChanges\\n  -> collect changes as []TreeChange\\n  -> ApplyTreeChanges(baseTreeHash, changes)  // O(depth * changed_dirs)\\n```\\n\\n### Detailed Changes\\n\\nThe `ApplyTreeChanges` function groups changes by their first path segment and recurses:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc ApplyTreeChanges(repo *git.Repository, rootTreeHash plumbing.Hash, changes []TreeChange) (plumbing.Hash, error) {\\n    if len(changes) == 0 {\\n        return rootTreeHash, nil\\n    }\\n\\n    // Read the current root tree\\n    var currentEntries []object.TreeEntry\\n    if rootTreeHash != plumbing.ZeroHash {\\n        tree, err := repo.TreeObject(rootTreeHash)\\n        if err != nil {\\n            return plumbing.ZeroHash, err\\n        }\\n        currentEntries = make([]object.TreeEntry, len(tree.Entries))\\n        copy(currentEntries, tree.Entries)\\n    }\\n\\n    // Group changes by first path segment\\n    type dirChanges struct {\\n        subChanges []TreeChange // Changes within this subdirectory (paths stripped of first segment)\\n        fileChange *TreeChange  // Direct file change at this level (nil if directory)\\n    }\\n    grouped := make(map[string]*dirChanges)\\n\\n    for i := range changes {\\n        c := changes[i]\\n        parts := strings.SplitN(c.Path, \\\"/\\\", 2)\\n        name := parts[0]\\n        if grouped[name] == nil {\\n            grouped[name] = &dirChanges{}\\n        }\\n        if len(parts) == 1 {\\n            // File at this level\\n            cc := c\\n            grouped[name].fileChange = &cc\\n        } else {\\n            // In a subdirectory\\n            grouped[name].subChanges = append(grouped[name].subChanges, TreeChange{\\n                Path:  parts[1],\\n                Entry: c.Entry,\\n            })\\n        }\\n    }\\n\\n    // Apply changes to current entries\\n    entryMap := make(map[string]object.TreeEntry, len(currentEntries))\\n    for _, e := range currentEntries {\\n        entryMap[e.Name] = e\\n    }\\n\\n    // Process each group\\n    for name, dc := range grouped {\\n        if dc.fileChange != nil {\\n            if dc.fileChange.Entry == nil {\\n                // Delete\\n                delete(entryMap, name)\\n            } else {\\n                // Add/update file\\n                entryMap[name] = *dc.fileChange.Entry\\n            }\\n        }\\n        if len(dc.subChanges) > 0 {\\n            // Recurse into subdirectory\\n            existingHash := plumbing.ZeroHash\\n            if existing, ok := entryMap[name]; ok && existing.Mode == filemode.Dir {\\n                existingHash = existing.Hash\\n            }\\n            newSubHash, err := ApplyTreeChanges(repo, existingHash, dc.subChanges)\\n            if err != nil {\\n                return plumbing.ZeroHash, err\\n            }\\n            entryMap[name] = object.TreeEntry{\\n                Name: name,\\n                Mode: filemode.Dir,\\n                Hash: newSubHash,\\n            }\\n        }\\n    }\\n\\n    // Convert back to slice and store\\n    result := make([]object.TreeEntry, 0, len(entryMap))\\n    for _, e := range entryMap {\\n        result = append(result, e)\\n    }\\n    sortTreeEntries(result)\\n    return storeTree(repo, result)\\n}\\n```\\n\\n### Rewrite `buildTreeWithChanges`\\n\\n```go\\nfunc (s *GitStore) buildTreeWithChanges(\\n    baseTreeHash plumbing.Hash,\\n    modifiedFiles, deletedFiles []string,\\n    metadataDir, metadataDirAbs string,\\n) (plumbing.Hash, error) {\\n    repoRoot, err := paths.RepoRoot()\\n    if err != nil {\\n        return plumbing.ZeroHash, fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to get repo root: %w\\\", err)\\n    }\\n\\n    var changes []TreeChange\\n\\n    // Deleted files\\n    for _, file := range deletedFiles {\\n        changes = append(changes, TreeChange{Path: file, Entry: nil})\\n    }\\n\\n    // Modified/new files\\n    for _, file := range modifiedFiles {\\n        absPath := filepath.Join(repoRoot, file)\\n        if !fileExists(absPath) {\\n            changes = append(changes, TreeChange{Path: file, Entry: nil})\\n            continue\\n        }\\n        blobHash, mode, err := createBlobFromFile(s.repo, absPath)\\n        if err != nil {\\n            continue\\n        }\\n        changes = append(changes, TreeChange{\\n            Path: file,\\n            Entry: &object.TreeEntry{\\n                Name: filepath.Base(file),\\n                Mode: mode,\\n                Hash: blobHash,\\n            },\\n        })\\n    }\\n\\n    // Metadata directory files\\n    if metadataDir != \\\"\\\" && metadataDirAbs != \\\"\\\" {\\n        metaChanges, err := collectMetadataChanges(s.repo, metadataDirAbs, metadataDir)\\n        if err != nil {\\n            return plumbing.ZeroHash, fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to collect metadata changes: %w\\\", err)\\n        }\\n        changes = append(changes, metaChanges...)\\n    }\\n\\n    if len(changes) == 0 {\\n        return baseTreeHash, nil\\n    }\\n\\n    return ApplyTreeChanges(s.repo, baseTreeHash, changes)\\n}\\n```\\n\\nWhere `collectMetadataChanges` walks the metadata directory (same logic as `addDirectoryToEntriesWithAbsPath`) but returns `[]TreeChange` instead of modifying a map.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 5. Refactoring `addTaskMetadataToTree`\\n\\n### Current Flow (temporary.go:291)\\n```\\naddTaskMetadataToTree\\n  -> FlattenTree(baseTree)         // SECOND flatten of the same tree!\\n  -> add task entries to flat map\\n  -> BuildTreeFromEntries()        // SECOND full rebuild\\n```\\n\\n### New Flow\\n```\\naddTaskMetadataToTree\\n  -> collect task entries as []TreeChange\\n  -> ApplyTreeChanges(baseTreeHash, changes)\\n```\\n\\nThis is straightforward since the task metadata entries are at a known path (`.entire/metadata/<sessionID>/tasks/<toolUseID>/...`).\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 6. Edge Cases\\n\\n### 6.1. First checkpoint on empty branch\\nWhen `ensureSessionsBranch()` creates a new orphan branch with an empty tree, `rootTreeHash` is the hash of an empty tree. `UpdateSubtree` handles this correctly because when `rootTreeHash` is zero or the tree has no entries, it creates new entries at each level.\\n\\n### 6.2. Multi-session checkpoints\\nThe `buildCheckpointSubtreeEntries` function reads the existing checkpoint tree at the shard path to detect existing sessions. It uses `tree.Tree(\\\"a3\\\").Tree(\\\"b2c4d5e6f7\\\")` to get the existing checkpoint tree, reads `metadata.json` for the `CheckpointSummary`, determines the session index (matching existing or new), and builds the session subtree. The `MergeKeepExisting` merge mode ensures that other sessions' subdirectories are preserved.\\n\\n### 6.3. Task checkpoints\\nTask checkpoint files go under `tasks/<toolUseID>/` within the checkpoint subdirectory. The `buildCheckpointSubtreeEntries` function includes these entries in the leaf tree. For `addTaskMetadataToTree` in the temporary path, this becomes a `TreeChange` at the appropriate path.\\n\\n### 6.4. `reaggregateFromEntries` needs the flat entries\\nThe `reaggregateFromEntries` function reads session metadata blobs from the flat entries map. In the new approach, we read session metadata directly from the existing checkpoint tree (which we already fetched for finding the session index). This avoids needing the flat map.\\n\\n### 6.5. `findSessionIndex` needs the flat entries\\nSame as above -- reads from the existing checkpoint tree directly, not the flat map.\\n\\n### 6.6. Stale file cleanup in `writeSessionToSubdirectory`\\nCurrently lines 300-304 of committed.go delete all existing entries at a session path to prevent stale files. In the tree surgery approach, when we build the session subdirectory, we use `ReplaceAll` merge mode for the session subfolder, which naturally replaces all contents.\\n\\n### 6.7. `copyMetadataDir`\\nThis function walks a filesystem directory and adds blobs. In the new approach, it produces entries that get added to the session subtree being built.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 7. Backward Compatibility\\n\\nThe tree surgery approach produces the **exact same tree structure** as the flatten+rebuild approach. The only difference is how the tree is constructed in memory:\\n- Same blob hashes (content is identical)\\n- Same tree structure (same directory hierarchy)\\n- Same tree hashes at every level (git tree hashes are content-addressed; same entries = same hash)\\n\\nThis means:\\n- `ReadCommitted`, `ReadSessionContent`, `ListCommitted` work without changes\\n- `ReadTemporary`, `GetTranscriptFromCommit` work without changes\\n- The `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch format is identical\\n- Shadow branch tree format is identical\\n\\n### Keeping `FlattenTree` and `BuildTreeFromEntries`\\n\\nThese functions are used by external callers (push_common.go, cleanup.go, content_overlap_test.go, session_test.go) and should be kept as-is. The new tree surgery functions are **additions**, not replacements. The old functions remain available for use cases where a full flatten+rebuild is the appropriate pattern (e.g., merge in push_common.go where two full trees need to be combined).\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 8. New Benchmarks\\n\\nAdd to `bench_test.go`:\\n\\n```go\\n// --- Tree Surgery benchmarks ---\\n// Isolates the UpdateSubtree cost which replaces FlattenTree+BuildTreeFromEntries.\\n\\nfunc BenchmarkUpdateSubtree(b *testing.B) {\\n    b.Run(\\\"EmptyBase\\\", benchUpdateSubtreeEmpty())\\n    b.Run(\\\"10Checkpoints\\\", benchUpdateSubtreeWithExisting(10))\\n    b.Run(\\\"100Checkpoints\\\", benchUpdateSubtreeWithExisting(100))\\n    b.Run(\\\"500Checkpoints\\\", benchUpdateSubtreeWithExisting(500))\\n}\\n\\nfunc BenchmarkApplyTreeChanges(b *testing.B) {\\n    b.Run(\\\"3Files_SmallRepo\\\", benchApplyTreeChanges(10, 3))\\n    b.Run(\\\"3Files_LargeRepo\\\", benchApplyTreeChanges(200, 3))\\n    b.Run(\\\"30Files_LargeRepo\\\", benchApplyTreeChanges(200, 30))\\n}\\n\\n// Compare old vs new for WriteCommitted\\nfunc BenchmarkWriteCommitted_TreeSurgery(b *testing.B) {\\n    b.Run(\\\"ManyPriorCheckpoints_OldPath\\\", benchWriteCommitted(200, 500, 15, 200))\\n    // The \\\"ManyPriorCheckpoints\\\" case from existing benchmarks now implicitly uses tree surgery\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe `benchUpdateSubtreeWithExisting` benchmark seeds N checkpoints on the metadata branch, then benchmarks adding one more checkpoint using `UpdateSubtree`. This directly measures the improvement: the old path is O(N), the new path should be O(1) (constant time regardless of N).\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 9. Implementation Sequence\\n\\n### Phase 1: Core tree surgery primitives (new file `tree_surgery.go`)\\n1. Add `TreeChange` type\\n2. Add `UpdateSubtreeOptions` and `MergeMode`\\n3. Implement `storeTree` helper (extract from `buildTreeObject`)\\n4. Implement `UpdateSubtree`\\n5. Implement `ApplyTreeChanges`\\n6. Add unit tests in `tree_surgery_test.go`\\n\\n### Phase 2: Refactor `WriteCommitted` path\\n1. Add `getSessionsBranchRef()` method\\n2. Add `buildCheckpointSubtreeEntries()` method that builds entries for a single checkpoint using tree reads (not flatten)\\n3. Refactor `writeStandardCheckpointEntries` to work with subtree approach (read existing checkpoint tree for session index, reaggregate from tree)\\n4. Replace `getSessionsBranchEntries()` + `BuildTreeFromEntries()` in `WriteCommitted`\\n5. Do the same for `UpdateCommitted` and `UpdateSummary`\\n6. Verify all existing tests pass unchanged\\n\\n### Phase 3: Refactor `buildTreeWithChanges` path\\n1. Add `collectMetadataChanges` helper (like `addDirectoryToEntriesWithAbsPath` but returns `[]TreeChange`)\\n2. Rewrite `buildTreeWithChanges` to use `ApplyTreeChanges`\\n3. Rewrite `addTaskMetadataToTree` to use `ApplyTreeChanges`\\n4. Verify all existing tests pass unchanged\\n\\n### Phase 4: Benchmarks\\n1. Add new benchmarks for `UpdateSubtree` and `ApplyTreeChanges`\\n2. Add comparative benchmarks showing improvement\\n3. Run `benchstat` to validate improvement\\n\\n### Phase 5: Cleanup (optional)\\n1. Mark `getSessionsBranchEntries` as deprecated (still used by tests, not removed)\\n2. Update CLAUDE.md checkpoint documentation\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 10. Key Design Decisions and Tradeoffs\\n\\n**Decision 1: Two separate APIs (`UpdateSubtree` and `ApplyTreeChanges`)**\\n- `UpdateSubtree` is optimized for the metadata branch case: replacing one directory deep in a tree.\\n- `ApplyTreeChanges` is optimized for the working tree case: modifying scattered files across the tree.\\n- Both avoid the flatten+rebuild pattern.\\n\\n**Decision 2: Keep `FlattenTree`/`BuildTreeFromEntries` alongside new functions**\\n- External callers (push_common.go, cleanup.go) use flatten+rebuild for legitimate reasons (merging two full trees, deleting scattered checkpoints).\\n- No breaking changes to the public API.\\n\\n**Decision 3: `MergeKeepExisting` mode for checkpoint writes**\\n- When writing a checkpoint to an existing shard bucket, other checkpoints in that bucket must be preserved.\\n- The `MergeKeepExisting` mode handles this naturally.\\n\\n**Decision 4: Read existing checkpoint tree for session indexing**\\n- Instead of scanning the flat entries map, read the checkpoint's tree directly with `tree.Tree(checkpointID.Path())`.\\n- This is 2-3 tree object reads instead of N*M flat map scans.\\n\\n**Potential risk: go-git object caching**\\n- go-git may or may not cache tree objects in memory. If it does, the `repo.TreeObject()` calls in `UpdateSubtree` are essentially free after the first read. If it doesn't, each call reads from the object store. Either way, reading a few specific tree objects is far cheaper than flattening the entire tree.\\n- The benchmarks will validate this empirically.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Critical Files for Implementation\\n- `/Users/evisdrenova/code/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/checkpoint/temporary.go` - Contains `FlattenTree`, `BuildTreeFromEntries`, `buildTreeWithChanges`, `addTaskMetadataToTree` -- the core functions to optimize and the location for new `ApplyTreeC